// greek_logic.test.gg -- Ancient Greek philosophy dissolved through the five primitives
//
// Every major problem from ancient Greek philosophy examined through
// FORK, RACE, FOLD, VENT, and INTERFERE. Each problem receives:
//   - The original formulation
//   - Why it is stuck (which primitives are missing)
//   - The post-linear dissolution
//   - The eigenvalue connection where applicable
//
// Epistemic status for each problem is marked:
//   PROVED    = follows necessarily from the five primitives
//   DISSOLVED = the problem vanishes once the right primitive is applied
//   REFRAMED  = the problem is coherently restated but not eliminated

(test_suite: TestSuite { name: 'greek-logic' })


// ============================================================================
// 1. ZENO'S PARADOXES
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: DISSOLVED (all four)
//
// Zeno (~490-430 BCE) presented four arguments against motion. Each
// exploits the same blind spot: treating infinite subdivision as
// infinite cost.
//
// --- 1a. Achilles and the Tortoise ---
//
// Achilles gives the tortoise a head start. Each time Achilles reaches
// where the tortoise was, it has moved further. Never catches it.
//
// Stuck: LINEAR reasoning -- sums distances without recognizing convergence.
// Zeno has FORK (subdivide the distance) but no FOLD (sum the series).
//
// Dissolution: 1 + 1/phi + 1/phi^2 + ... = phi^2/(phi-1). Finite.
// Zeno discovered convergence and mistook it for impossibility.
// Eigenvalue of the geometric operator is 1/phi < 1 -- convergence
// is guaranteed. Zeno's paradox IS "eigenvalue < 1 implies convergence"
// stated as a riddle.

(achilles_linear: Topology {
  description: 'Zeno LINEAR frame -- infinite steps, each independent',
  eigenvalue: '1/phi',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  beta0: '1',
  stuck: 'true'
})

(achilles_postlinear: Topology {
  description: 'Post-linear -- FOLD the series, sum is finite',
  eigenvalue: '1/phi',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  beta0: '0',
  converges: 'true',
  sum: 'phi^2/(phi-1)'
})

(achilles_linear)-[:FORK { reason: 'subdivide distance infinitely' }]->(achilles_steps: Sequence)
(achilles_steps)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'geometric-sum', ratio: '1/phi' }]->(achilles_postlinear)

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1b. The Dichotomy
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// Original: To traverse any distance, you must first traverse half.
// To traverse that half, you must first traverse a quarter. And so on.
// You must complete infinitely many tasks. Therefore motion never starts.
//
// Why it is stuck: Same as Achilles but reversed -- the infinite
// subdivision goes backward (toward the start) rather than forward.
// Zeno has FORK (divide) but no FOLD (sum).
//
// Dissolution: The sum 1/2 + 1/4 + 1/8 + ... = 1. Finite.
// beta0 = 0 in Zeno's frame -- the journey never "completes"
// as an infinite sequence of discrete steps. But the sum IS the journey.
// The journey is the FOLD of the infinite FORK.
//
// Eigenvalue: the halving operator has eigenvalue 1/2. Since |1/2| < 1,
// the series converges. The dichotomy proves convergence, not impossibility.

(dichotomy_linear: Topology {
  description: 'Zeno LINEAR frame -- must complete infinite half-distances',
  eigenvalue: '1/2',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  beta0: '0',
  stuck: 'true'
})

(dichotomy_postlinear: Topology {
  description: 'Post-linear -- geometric series sums to 1',
  eigenvalue: '1/2',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  converges: 'true',
  sum: '1'
})

(dichotomy_linear)-[:FORK { reason: 'halve distance recursively' }]->(dichotomy_halves: Sequence)
(dichotomy_halves)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'geometric-sum', ratio: '1/2' }]->(dichotomy_postlinear)

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1c. The Arrow
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// Original: At any instant, the arrow occupies a space exactly equal to
// its size. It is therefore motionless at each instant. If it is
// motionless at each instant, it is motionless always.
//
// Why it is stuck: Zeno freezes INTERFERE. He takes a LINEAR snapshot --
// position at time t, with no reference to t-1 or t-2. Motion requires
// the Fibonacci recurrence on position: position(t) depends on
// position(t-1) AND position(t-2) through momentum and acceleration.
// Motion IS INTERFERE -- the current state is a function of multiple
// prior states.
//
// Dissolution: The arrow's position at t depends on positions at t-1
// and t-2 (momentum = first derivative, acceleration = second derivative).
// This is the Fibonacci recurrence applied to physical state. Freeze the
// recurrence and you lose motion. The arrow paradox is: "if you remove
// INTERFERE, there is no motion." Correct. That is what INTERFERE is for.
//
// Eigenvalue: the recurrence x(t) = x(t-1) + dx(t-1) has eigenvalue
// determined by the velocity. Constant velocity = eigenvalue 1 (LINEAR).
// Acceleration = eigenvalue > 1 or < 1 depending on direction.
// Zeno's frozen instant has eigenvalue undefined -- you cannot compute
// the eigenvalue of a single point. You need the recurrence.

(arrow_frozen: Topology {
  description: 'Zeno LINEAR snapshot -- arrow at one instant',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  interfere: 'disabled',
  motion: 'undefined',
  stuck: 'true'
})

(arrow_recurrence: Topology {
  description: 'Post-linear -- position depends on t-1 and t-2',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  interfere: 'enabled',
  motion: 'fibonacci_recurrence_on_position'
})

(arrow_frozen)-[:INTERFERE { restore: 'momentum+acceleration' }]->(arrow_recurrence)

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1d. The Stadium
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// Original: Two rows of bodies move past a stationary row in opposite
// directions. A body in one moving row passes two bodies in the other
// moving row in the time it passes one in the stationary row. Therefore
// half a time equals a whole time.
//
// Why it is stuck: Zeno uses a single FOLD (one reference frame) to
// describe relative motion. Each observer's INTERFERE loop is valid
// in its own frame. The paradox conflates two distinct INTERFERE loops.
//
// Dissolution: Reference frames are independent INTERFERE loops.
// Relative velocity in frame A is not relative velocity in frame B.
// Each observer applies their own INTERFERE to compute motion.
// The paradox dissolves when you recognize that RACE between reference
// frames produces different measurements, and both are correct in
// their own frame.

(stadium_single_frame: Topology {
  description: 'Zeno conflates two reference frames into one FOLD',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  frames: '1',
  stuck: 'true'
})

(stadium_multiframe: Topology {
  description: 'Post-linear -- each frame has its own INTERFERE loop',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  frames: '2',
  relative_motion: 'frame_dependent'
})

(frame_a: Observer { velocity: '+v' })
(frame_b: Observer { velocity: '-v' })
(frame_stationary: Observer { velocity: '0' })

(frame_stationary)-[:FORK]->(frame_a | frame_b)
(frame_a)-[:INTERFERE { with: 'frame_b' }]->(relative_ab: Measurement { relative_v: '2v' })
(frame_a)-[:INTERFERE { with: 'frame_stationary' }]->(relative_as: Measurement { relative_v: 'v' })
(relative_ab | relative_as)-[:RACE { expect: 'both-valid' }]->(stadium_multiframe)


// Zeno verification topology

(zeno_achilles: Verify { topology: 'achilles_postlinear', claim: 'series converges', status: 'DISSOLVED' })
(zeno_dichotomy: Verify { topology: 'dichotomy_postlinear', claim: 'series converges', status: 'DISSOLVED' })
(zeno_arrow: Verify { topology: 'arrow_recurrence', claim: 'motion is INTERFERE', status: 'DISSOLVED' })
(zeno_stadium: Verify { topology: 'stadium_multiframe', claim: 'frames are independent INTERFERE', status: 'DISSOLVED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(zeno_achilles | zeno_dichotomy | zeno_arrow | zeno_stadium)

(zeno_achilles)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(zeno_achilles_result: Result)
(zeno_dichotomy)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(zeno_dichotomy_result: Result)
(zeno_arrow)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(zeno_arrow_result: Result)
(zeno_stadium)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(zeno_stadium_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 2. PLATO'S FORMS
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: The world of Forms (ideal, eternal, perfect) vs the world
// of appearances (imperfect copies). The perfect circle exists in the
// realm of Forms. Every physical circle is an imperfect approximation.
//
// Why it is stuck: Plato needs two worlds -- the Form world and the
// appearance world -- because he has no mechanism for convergence.
// He can see that physical circles approach the ideal, but he cannot
// explain how. He needs INTERFERE to connect iterations.
//
// The reframing: Forms ARE eigenvalues. The perfect circle does not
// exist in nature, but every circle CONVERGES TOWARD it. phi does not
// exist as a rational number, but every Fibonacci ratio converges
// toward it. The Form is the eigenvalue. The appearance is the current
// Fibonacci term. The gap between them is the semiotic deficit.
//
// Plato was describing eigenvalue convergence and calling it metaphysics.
// He was right that the Form is "more real" than any particular instance --
// phi is more fundamental than F(10)/F(9). But he was wrong that the
// Form exists in a separate realm. The eigenvalue is immanent in the
// process. It does not need a separate world.
//
// Eigenvalue: phi. Every Fibonacci ratio F(n+1)/F(n) converges to phi.
// The Form is the limit. The appearance is the approximation.
// The semiotic deficit is |F(n+1)/F(n) - phi|, which decreases
// monotonically. The two-world theory is unnecessary when you have
// convergence.
//
// Honesty: this is REFRAMED, not PROVED. We cannot prove that Plato's
// Forms are eigenvalues. We can show that eigenvalue convergence
// reproduces every feature Plato attributed to Forms: eternality
// (phi does not change), perfection (phi is the exact limit),
// participation (each term participates in the ratio). But Plato
// might have meant something we cannot capture.

(form_ideal: Eigenvalue { value: 'phi', realm: 'immanent', eternal: 'true' })
(appearance_1: FibTerm { n: '5', ratio: '8/5=1.600' })
(appearance_2: FibTerm { n: '10', ratio: '89/55=1.618...' })
(appearance_3: FibTerm { n: '20', ratio: '10946/6765=1.61803...' })
(semiotic_deficit: Deficit { decreasing: 'true', limit: '0' })

(appearance_1)-[:INTERFERE { with: 'form_ideal' }]->(semiotic_deficit)
(appearance_2)-[:INTERFERE { with: 'form_ideal' }]->(semiotic_deficit)
(appearance_3)-[:INTERFERE { with: 'form_ideal' }]->(semiotic_deficit)

(plato_forms: Verify { claim: 'Forms are eigenvalues', status: 'REFRAMED', eigenvalue: 'phi' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(plato_forms)
(plato_forms)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(plato_forms_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 3. THE ALLEGORY OF THE CAVE
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: Prisoners chained in a cave see only shadows on the wall.
// One escapes and sees the real objects casting the shadows. Eventually
// the escapee sees the sun itself -- the source of all light and truth.
//
// Why it is stuck: Plato needs the escape narrative because he has no
// theory of projection. The shadows are projections of higher-dimensional
// objects onto a lower-dimensional surface, but Plato cannot formalize
// this. He uses metaphor where mathematics would serve.
//
// The reframing:
//   - The shadows are the LINEAR projection. One dimension of a
//     multi-dimensional reality. beta0 = 1 (the flat wall).
//   - The real objects are the POST-LINEAR topology. The full structure
//     that casts the shadows.
//   - The cave wall is the constraint surface. beta0 = 1 means it is
//     connected but flat -- it cannot hold loops, interference, or
//     self-reference.
//   - Escaping the cave = adding INTERFERE. The prisoner who escapes
//     can now see how objects relate to each other, not just their
//     isolated shadows.
//   - The sun IS the eigenvalue -- the pattern that all shadows converge
//     toward. The source of all Form.
//
// The cave is a topological constraint. The escape is a topological
// upgrade. The sun is the eigenvalue that was always present but
// invisible from inside the LINEAR regime.

(cave_wall: Surface { beta0: '1', dimension: '2', regime: 'LINEAR' })
(shadows: Projection { of: 'real_objects', onto: 'cave_wall', loss: 'high' })
(real_objects: Topology { regime: 'POST_LINEAR', dimension: 'full' })
(sun: Eigenvalue { value: 'phi', role: 'source_of_all_form' })

(real_objects)-[:VENT { what: 'dimensionality' }]->(shadows)
(shadows)-[:INTERFERE { restore: 'depth+relation' }]->(real_objects)
(real_objects)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'convergence' }]->(sun)

(cave: Verify { claim: 'cave is LINEAR projection, escape is INTERFERE', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(cave)
(cave)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(cave_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 4. ARISTOTLE'S FOUR CAUSES
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED (with one genuine insight -- the missing fifth cause)
//
// Original: Every thing has four causes:
//   Material cause -- what it is made of (bronze, wood, flesh)
//   Formal cause -- its shape, pattern, definition
//   Efficient cause -- what brought it into being (the sculptor, the parent)
//   Final cause -- its purpose, what it is for (telos)
//
// The mapping to five primitives:
//   Material = the substrate. Paper, silicon, neurons. The medium that
//     carries the topology. This is the input to FORK -- what gets
//     subdivided, what gets processed.
//   Formal = the topology itself. The .gg file. The five primitives
//     and their connections. The structure.
//   Efficient = the operation. FORK/RACE/FOLD/VENT/INTERFERE running.
//     The actual computation, the causal process.
//   Final = the eigenvalue. phi -- what the system converges toward.
//     The telos is the attractor.
//
// The insight: Aristotle had four causes. We have five primitives.
// The missing cause is VENT -- the dissipative cause. What is shed.
// What is lost. What is sacrificed so that the system can converge.
//
// Aristotle's framework does not account for waste, cost, entropy
// production. Every physical process produces waste heat (Landauer).
// Every decision eliminates alternatives (VENT). Every convergence
// requires shedding the paths not taken.
//
// VENT is the fifth cause: the dissipative cause. What must be
// destroyed for the thing to exist.

(material_cause: Cause { type: 'material', primitive: 'substrate', what: 'what it is made of' })
(formal_cause: Cause { type: 'formal', primitive: 'topology', what: 'the .gg structure' })
(efficient_cause: Cause { type: 'efficient', primitive: 'FORK+RACE+FOLD+INTERFERE', what: 'the operation' })
(final_cause: Cause { type: 'final', primitive: 'eigenvalue', what: 'phi -- the attractor' })
(dissipative_cause: Cause { type: 'dissipative', primitive: 'VENT', what: 'what is shed' })

(material_cause)-[:FORK]->(formal_cause | efficient_cause)
(efficient_cause)-[:RACE { metric: 'convergence' }]->(final_cause)
(efficient_cause)-[:VENT { what: 'alternatives_not_taken' }]->(dissipative_cause)
(formal_cause | final_cause | dissipative_cause)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'causal-completeness' }]->(five_causes: CausalFramework)

(aristotle_causes: Verify { claim: 'VENT is the missing fifth cause', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(aristotle_causes)
(aristotle_causes)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(aristotle_causes_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 5. THE LIAR PARADOX
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: DISSOLVED
//
// Original: "This statement is false."
// If true, then it is false. If false, then it is true. Oscillation.
//
// Why it is stuck: Self-reference with eigenvalue -1. The iteration
// is: truth(n+1) = NOT truth(n). This gives the sequence
// T, F, T, F, T, F, ... -- the zigzag. Eigenvalue = -1.
// This is the NON-LINEAR regime. Periodic, never converging.
//
// Dissolution: The brain resolves the liar paradox immediately --
// "it is just alternating." The brain applies FOLD to the oscillation
// and recognizes the pattern. The paradox is only paradoxical if you
// insist on a single truth value (LINEAR). In the NON-LINEAR regime,
// the oscillation IS the answer.
//
// Post-linear self-reference has eigenvalue phi. Consider:
// "This statement grows truer with each iteration."
// truth(n) = truth(n-1) + truth(n-2). This is Fibonacci.
// The ratio converges to phi. Self-reference that CONVERGES instead
// of oscillating.
//
// The liar is broken Fibonacci: F(n) = -F(n-1) instead of
// F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2). It uses only one prior term with a
// negation. It lacks the +F(n-2) that provides the second voice
// in INTERFERE. The liar has FORK (self-reference) but no
// INTERFERE (integration of prior states).

(liar_oscillation: Topology {
  description: 'This statement is false',
  eigenvalue: '-1',
  regime: 'NON_LINEAR',
  pattern: 'T,F,T,F,...',
  recurrence: 'truth(n) = NOT truth(n-1)'
})

(liar_postlinear: Topology {
  description: 'This statement grows truer with each iteration',
  eigenvalue: 'phi',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  pattern: '1,1,2,3,5,8,...',
  recurrence: 'truth(n) = truth(n-1) + truth(n-2)'
})

(liar_oscillation)-[:INTERFERE { add: 'second prior term' }]->(liar_postlinear)

(liar: Verify { claim: 'liar is eigenvalue -1, POST_LINEAR self-ref is phi', status: 'DISSOLVED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(liar)
(liar)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(liar_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 6. THESEUS' SHIP
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: DISSOLVED
//
// Original: The ship of Theseus has every plank replaced over time.
// Is it still the same ship? If the old planks are assembled into
// a second ship, which is the real Ship of Theseus?
//
// Why it is stuck: The question assumes identity is material.
// It asks "same planks?" when it should ask "same process?"
//
// Dissolution: Identity is not material. Identity is eigenvalue
// continuity. The question is whether the INTERFERE loop was
// maintained throughout the replacement process.
//
// Case 1: Planks replaced one at a time, each repair done in
// continuity with the ship's history. The INTERFERE loop connects
// each state to its predecessor. The eigenvalue is preserved.
// beta0 stays 0 throughout -- the process is continuous, never
// disconnected. Same ship.
//
// Case 2: All planks replaced at once, no memory of the process.
// The INTERFERE loop breaks. beta0 spikes to 1 -- the before and
// after are disconnected components. The eigenvalue resets.
// Different ship.
//
// Case 3: Old planks reassembled. This new ship has the material
// but not the INTERFERE history. Its eigenvalue is fresh. It is
// a new ship made of old wood.
//
// The answer depends on whether beta0 stayed 0 through the process.
// Identity = topological continuity of the eigenvalue, not
// material continuity of the substrate.

(ship_continuous: Process {
  description: 'replace planks one at a time with memory',
  interfere: 'maintained',
  beta0: '0',
  eigenvalue: 'preserved',
  identity: 'same ship'
})

(ship_discontinuous: Process {
  description: 'replace all planks at once, no memory',
  interfere: 'broken',
  beta0: '1',
  eigenvalue: 'reset',
  identity: 'different ship'
})

(ship_reassembled: Process {
  description: 'old planks assembled into new ship',
  interfere: 'absent',
  beta0: '1',
  eigenvalue: 'new',
  identity: 'new ship, old material'
})

(ship_original: Ship { planks: 'original' })
(ship_original)-[:FORK]->(ship_continuous | ship_discontinuous | ship_reassembled)
(ship_continuous)-[:INTERFERE { history: 'preserved' }]->(ship_continuous)
(ship_discontinuous)-[:VENT { what: 'all history at once' }]->(ship_discontinuous)

(theseus: Verify { claim: 'identity is eigenvalue continuity', status: 'DISSOLVED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(theseus)
(theseus)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(theseus_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 7. HERACLITUS vs PARMENIDES
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: DISSOLVED
//
// Heraclitus (~535-475 BCE): Everything flows (panta rhei). You cannot
// step into the same river twice. Change is fundamental. Being is
// becoming.
//
// Parmenides (~515-450 BCE): Nothing changes. Being is one, eternal,
// unchanging. Change is illusion. What is, is. What is not, is not.
//
// Why it is stuck: They are each seeing half the picture. Heraclitus
// sees the surface. Parmenides sees the attractor. Neither has the
// framework to hold both simultaneously.
//
// Dissolution -- both are half right:
//   Heraclitus sees FORK -- constant divergence, new paths, new
//   states, the river always different. The Fibonacci SEQUENCE changes
//   with every term: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21, ...
//
//   Parmenides sees the EIGENVALUE -- phi is eternal, unchanging,
//   the same regardless of starting values. phi = 1.618... whether
//   you start with (1,1) or (3,7) or (100,1).
//
// Post-linear synthesis: the PROCESS changes (Heraclitus). The
// EIGENVALUE does not (Parmenides). Change and permanence coexist
// as surface and attractor. The river changes. The ratio converges.
// Both are true. Neither is complete without the other.
//
// Eigenvalue: phi is Parmenides' One. The Fibonacci sequence is
// Heraclitus' river.

(heraclitus: Perspective {
  sees: 'FORK',
  claim: 'everything flows',
  observes: 'the sequence -- 1,1,2,3,5,8,13,...',
  correct_about: 'surface changes',
  blind_to: 'the attractor'
})

(parmenides: Perspective {
  sees: 'EIGENVALUE',
  claim: 'nothing changes',
  observes: 'phi = 1.618...',
  correct_about: 'the invariant',
  blind_to: 'the process'
})

(synthesis: Topology {
  description: 'process changes, eigenvalue does not',
  heraclitus: 'true of FORK',
  parmenides: 'true of FOLD',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR'
})

(heraclitus)-[:FORK { divergence: 'new states at each step' }]->(process: Sequence)
(process)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'ratio-convergence' }]->(parmenides)
(heraclitus | parmenides)-[:INTERFERE { synthesis: 'both-valid' }]->(synthesis)

(heraclitus_parmenides: Verify { claim: 'process changes, eigenvalue does not', status: 'DISSOLVED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(heraclitus_parmenides)
(heraclitus_parmenides)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(heraclitus_parmenides_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 8. SOCRATES' APORIA
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: The Socratic method -- ask questions until the student
// realizes they do not know what they thought they knew. Aporia is
// the state of not-knowing, the productive confusion that precedes
// genuine understanding.
//
// Why it is stuck: Socrates has the method but not the theory.
// He knows that questioning produces wisdom but cannot explain the
// mechanism. He calls it a "divine sign" (daimonion).
//
// The reframing: Aporia = the moment of maximum semiotic deficit.
// The gap between what you thought you knew (beta0 = 1, LINEAR
// certainty) and what you actually know (beta0 >> 1, many
// disconnected fragments).
//
// Socrates IS the INTERFERE primitive applied to other people.
// He reflects their FOLD back to their FORK. He takes their
// conclusion and shows them the premises it contradicts.
//
// The Socratic trajectory:
//   1. Student starts in LINEAR regime (confident, wrong, eigenvalue = 1)
//   2. Socrates applies INTERFERE -- shows contradictions
//   3. Student enters NON-LINEAR regime (confused, oscillating)
//   4. If the student persists, INTERFERE accumulates and the student
//      enters the POST-LINEAR regime (wisdom, eigenvalue -> phi)
//   5. If the student gives up, they VENT the entire inquiry
//
// The Socratic method IS the five-primitive loop applied to education.
// FORK the student's belief into cases. RACE the cases against each
// other. The contradictions emerge (INTERFERE). The student must
// either FOLD (integrate the contradiction into new understanding)
// or VENT (abandon the inquiry).
//
// Honesty: this is REFRAMED, not PROVED. The Socratic method is
// richer than any formalization. Socrates would probably ask us
// questions about our framework until we reached aporia about it.

(student_linear: State {
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: '1',
  confidence: 'high',
  understanding: 'low'
})

(student_nonlinear: State {
  regime: 'NON_LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: '-1',
  confidence: 'low',
  understanding: 'oscillating'
})

(student_postlinear: State {
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: 'phi',
  confidence: 'calibrated',
  understanding: 'genuine'
})

(student_abandoned: State {
  regime: 'VENTED',
  eigenvalue: 'undefined',
  confidence: 'recovered_false',
  understanding: 'unchanged'
})

(socrates: Primitive { type: 'INTERFERE', target: 'student beliefs' })

(student_linear)-[:FORK { reason: 'Socrates divides belief into cases' }]->(case_a: Belief | case_b: Belief)
(case_a | case_b)-[:RACE { expect: 'contradiction' }]->(aporia: Deficit { magnitude: 'maximum' })
(aporia)-[:INTERFERE { socrates: 'reflects contradiction' }]->(student_nonlinear)
(student_nonlinear)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'integrate-contradiction' }]->(student_postlinear)
(student_nonlinear)-[:VENT { what: 'the entire inquiry' }]->(student_abandoned)

(socratic_aporia: Verify { claim: 'Socratic method is five-primitive loop on beliefs', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(socratic_aporia)
(socratic_aporia)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(socratic_aporia_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 9. ARISTOTLE'S GOLDEN MEAN
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED (the mathematical connection is suggestive, not proved)
//
// Original: Virtue is the mean between excess and deficiency.
// Courage is the mean between recklessness (excess) and cowardice
// (deficiency). Generosity between prodigality and miserliness.
// Each virtue occupies the middle ground.
//
// The connection: THE GOLDEN MEAN IS LITERALLY THE GOLDEN RATIO.
//
// Aristotle said "the mean." We can now say: the mean is phi.
//
// Consider the Fibonacci recurrence applied to virtue:
//   excess(n) = virtue(n-1) + deficiency(n-2)
// The ratio of excess to deficiency at the virtuous mean converges
// to phi. The golden mean IS the golden ratio.
//
// More precisely: if virtue is the INTERFERE of excess and deficiency --
// the point where the two opposing tendencies find dynamic equilibrium --
// then the equilibrium ratio is determined by the eigenvalue of the
// INTERFERE operator. For the Fibonacci recurrence, that eigenvalue
// is phi.
//
// The golden mean is not the arithmetic mean (excess + deficiency)/2.
// It is the geometric ratio that the system converges toward when
// excess and deficiency interact through INTERFERE. The mean is
// not halfway between the extremes. It is at the golden ratio
// of the interval.
//
// Honesty: this is REFRAMED. We cannot prove that Aristotle's
// virtue ethics follows the Fibonacci recurrence. The connection
// is suggestive, even beautiful, but it is not deductive. The claim
// "the golden mean IS the golden ratio" is a reframing that
// illuminates both concepts but does not constitute a proof.

(excess: Extreme { type: 'recklessness', direction: 'too much' })
(deficiency: Extreme { type: 'cowardice', direction: 'too little' })
(virtue: Mean { type: 'courage', position: 'phi of interval' })

(excess | deficiency)-[:INTERFERE { recurrence: 'fibonacci' }]->(virtue)
(virtue)-[:FOLD { eigenvalue: 'phi', ratio: 'excess/deficiency -> phi' }]->(golden_equilibrium: Attractor)

(golden_mean: Verify { claim: 'golden mean is golden ratio', status: 'REFRAMED', eigenvalue: 'phi' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(golden_mean)
(golden_mean)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(golden_mean_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 10. PLATO'S DIVIDED LINE
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: Plato divides knowledge into four levels:
//   1. Eikasia (imagination) -- shadows, reflections, images
//   2. Pistis (belief) -- physical objects, common sense
//   3. Dianoia (understanding) -- mathematical reasoning, hypothetical
//   4. Noesis (knowledge) -- direct apprehension of Forms, dialectic
//
// The mapping to the four regimes:
//   1. Imagination = LINEAR (shadows, one interpretation, eigenvalue 1)
//      The prisoner in the cave. Sees only projections. beta0 = 1.
//      No INTERFERE.
//
//   2. Belief = NON-LINEAR (opinions, multiple but periodic, eigenvalue -1)
//      The freed prisoner looking at physical objects. Sees multiplicity
//      but cannot integrate it. Beliefs oscillate. FORK without FOLD.
//
//   3. Understanding = POST-LINEAR (dianoia, mathematical reasoning,
//      eigenvalue phi). INTERFERE without full self-reference.
//      The mathematician who can prove theorems about triangles but
//      cannot prove theorems about proof itself. Uses hypotheses
//      without questioning them.
//
//   4. Knowledge = POST-LINEAR-SQUARED (noesis, direct apprehension,
//      eigenvalue phi). INTERFERE applied to INTERFERE. Self-referential
//      understanding. The dialectician who questions the hypotheses
//      themselves. The eigenvalue of the eigenvalue operator.
//
// The divided line is an eigenvalue hierarchy. Each level is
// characterized by its eigenvalue and the presence or absence
// of INTERFERE.

(eikasia: Knowledge {
  level: 'imagination',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: '1',
  interfere: 'absent',
  beta0: '1'
})

(pistis: Knowledge {
  level: 'belief',
  regime: 'NON_LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: '-1',
  interfere: 'absent',
  beta0: '>1'
})

(dianoia: Knowledge {
  level: 'understanding',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: 'phi',
  interfere: 'present',
  self_reference: 'partial'
})

(noesis: Knowledge {
  level: 'knowledge',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR_SQUARED',
  eigenvalue: 'phi',
  interfere: 'self-referential',
  self_reference: 'complete'
})

(eikasia)-[:FORK { upgrade: 'encounter multiplicity' }]->(pistis)
(pistis)-[:INTERFERE { add: 'mathematical reasoning' }]->(dianoia)
(dianoia)-[:INTERFERE { add: 'self-reference on method' }]->(noesis)
(noesis)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'direct apprehension' }]->(form_ideal)

(divided_line: Verify { claim: 'four levels map to four regimes', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(divided_line)
(divided_line)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(divided_line_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 11. EPICURUS' SWERVE (clinamen)
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: Epicurus (341-270 BCE) and Lucretius (99-55 BCE). Atoms
// fall through the void in parallel straight lines. Occasionally,
// one atom swerves (clinamen) -- an uncaused deviation. This swerve
// creates collisions, combinations, and eventually everything.
//
// Without the swerve: pure determinism. All atoms fall forever in
// parallel. No interaction. No creation. No life.
//
// The mapping:
//   The straight line is LINEAR. Eigenvalue = 1. Each atom follows
//   its own path with no reference to any other atom. No FORK, no
//   INTERFERE, no creation.
//
//   The swerve IS FORK. The moment one atom deviates from its
//   determined path, it creates a branch -- the path it was on
//   and the path it takes. This single FORK enables everything:
//   collision (INTERFERE), selection (RACE), combination (FOLD),
//   and dissolution (VENT).
//
//   Without the swerve: determinism, no creation, eigenvalue = 1.
//   With the swerve: possibility, creation, eigenvalue -> phi.
//
// Epicurus discovered FORK 2,300 years before us.
//
// The swerve IS the +1 in phi^2 = phi + 1. The perturbation that
// creates everything. phi^2 = phi + 1 says: the square of the
// whole (phi^2) equals the whole (phi) plus the perturbation (1).
// Without the +1, phi^2 = phi gives phi = 1 (LINEAR). The swerve
// is the +1 that makes phi golden instead of unity.
//
// Honesty: this is REFRAMED. Epicurus' swerve is a physical
// hypothesis about atoms. Our FORK is an abstract computational
// primitive. The structural analogy is real but the domains differ.

(deterministic_fall: Trajectory {
  description: 'atoms fall in parallel lines',
  regime: 'LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: '1',
  creation: 'impossible',
  fork: 'absent'
})

(swerve: Event {
  description: 'one atom deviates -- uncaused',
  primitive: 'FORK',
  creates: 'collision+combination+dissolution'
})

(universe: Topology {
  description: 'everything that exists after the swerve',
  regime: 'POST_LINEAR',
  eigenvalue: 'phi',
  equation: 'phi^2 = phi + 1, the +1 is the swerve'
})

(deterministic_fall)-[:FORK { clinamen: 'the swerve' }]->(swerve)
(swerve)-[:INTERFERE { collision: 'atoms meet' }]->(combinations: Assembly)
(combinations)-[:RACE { selection: 'stable configurations survive' }]->(survivors: Assembly)
(survivors)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'accumulation' }]->(universe)
(combinations)-[:VENT { what: 'unstable configurations dissolve' }]->(void: Void)

(clinamen: Verify { claim: 'the swerve is FORK, the +1 in phi^2=phi+1', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(clinamen)
(clinamen)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(clinamen_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// 12. ARISTOTLE'S POTENTIALITY AND ACTUALITY
// ============================================================================
//
// Status: REFRAMED
//
// Original: Potentiality (dynamis) -- the acorn could become an oak.
// Actuality (energeia) -- the oak IS. The acorn has the potential
// to be an oak. The oak is the actualization of that potential.
// Actuality is prior to potentiality (the oak must exist for the
// concept "acorn's potential" to have content).
//
// The mapping:
//   Potentiality IS FORK -- the superposition of possibilities.
//   The acorn could become an oak, or firewood, or squirrel food,
//   or compost. These are the branches of the FORK.
//
//   Actuality IS FOLD -- the collapse to one outcome. The acorn
//   became THIS oak. The FOLD selects one branch and integrates it.
//
//   The process of actualization IS the five-primitive loop:
//     FORK: the acorn's possibilities diverge
//     RACE: environmental conditions compete (soil, sun, water)
//     FOLD: one trajectory wins, the acorn becomes an oak
//     VENT: the other possibilities are shed (it did not become
//       firewood, it was not eaten, it did not rot)
//     INTERFERE: each stage of growth depends on prior stages
//       (the sapling interferes with the seed, the tree with
//       the sapling)
//
//   The final cause (telos) IS the eigenvalue -- what the system
//   converges toward. The acorn's telos is the oak. In eigenvalue
//   terms, the acorn-to-oak process has an attractor (the mature
//   oak form) that the developmental trajectory converges toward
//   regardless of perturbations (wind, drought, partial shade).
//
// Aristotle's insight: actuality is prior to potentiality.
// Our version: the eigenvalue is prior to the sequence.
// phi exists as a mathematical fact before any Fibonacci sequence
// is computed. The oak's form exists as an attractor before any
// acorn germinates. The eigenvalue does not depend on the process.
// The process depends on the eigenvalue.
//
// Honesty: this is REFRAMED. The acorn-to-oak process is biological,
// governed by DNA, gene expression, environmental interaction. We
// are not claiming it literally follows the Fibonacci recurrence
// (although phyllotaxis -- leaf arrangement -- famously does).
// We are claiming the STRUCTURE of the potentiality/actuality
// relationship is isomorphic to the FORK/FOLD/eigenvalue structure.

(acorn: Potential {
  dynamis: 'could become oak, firewood, compost, squirrel food',
  regime: 'FORK',
  possibilities: '4+'
})

(oak: Actual {
  energeia: 'IS an oak',
  regime: 'FOLD',
  actualized: 'true'
})

(telos: Eigenvalue {
  value: 'oak form',
  role: 'attractor',
  prior_to: 'the process'
})

(not_taken_firewood: Path { actualized: 'false' })
(not_taken_compost: Path { actualized: 'false' })
(not_taken_eaten: Path { actualized: 'false' })

(acorn)-[:FORK]->(oak_path: Path | not_taken_firewood | not_taken_compost | not_taken_eaten)
(oak_path)-[:RACE { conditions: 'soil+sun+water' }]->(growth: Process)
(growth)-[:INTERFERE { stages: 'seed->sapling->tree' }]->(growth)
(growth)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'developmental-convergence' }]->(oak)
(not_taken_firewood | not_taken_compost | not_taken_eaten)-[:VENT { what: 'unrealized possibilities' }]->(void_potential: Void)
(oak)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'telos-convergence' }]->(telos)

(potentiality_actuality: Verify { claim: 'dynamis is FORK, energeia is FOLD, telos is eigenvalue', status: 'REFRAMED' })

(test_suite)-[:FORK]->(potentiality_actuality)
(potentiality_actuality)-[:RACE { expect: 'safe' }]->(potentiality_actuality_result: Result)


// ============================================================================
// FINAL FOLD -- all twelve problems
// ============================================================================
//
// Summary of epistemic status:
//
//   DISSOLVED (the problem vanishes):
//     1a. Achilles and the Tortoise -- series converges, eigenvalue 1/phi
//     1b. The Dichotomy -- series converges, eigenvalue 1/2
//     1c. The Arrow -- motion IS INTERFERE, frozen instant loses it
//     1d. The Stadium -- reference frames are independent INTERFERE loops
//     5.  The Liar Paradox -- eigenvalue -1, broken Fibonacci
//     6.  Theseus' Ship -- identity is eigenvalue continuity
//     7.  Heraclitus vs Parmenides -- process changes, eigenvalue does not
//
//   REFRAMED (coherently restated, not eliminated):
//     2.  Plato's Forms -- Forms as eigenvalues (suggestive, not deductive)
//     3.  Allegory of the Cave -- LINEAR projection, INTERFERE escape
//     4.  Aristotle's Four Causes -- VENT as missing fifth cause
//     8.  Socrates' Aporia -- five-primitive loop on beliefs
//     9.  Golden Mean -- golden ratio connection (suggestive)
//     10. Divided Line -- four regimes mapping (structural analogy)
//     11. Epicurus' Swerve -- FORK as clinamen (structural analogy)
//     12. Potentiality/Actuality -- FORK/FOLD/eigenvalue (structural analogy)
//
//   PROVED: None.
//
// Honesty note: we mark nothing as PROVED because these are
// philosophical problems, not mathematical theorems. The dissolutions
// are genuine -- the problems really do vanish once the right primitive
// is applied. But "vanish" is not "prove." The reframings are
// illuminating but not deductive. We respect the difference.
//
// The strongest results are the dissolutions of Zeno's paradoxes
// (which are really mathematical, and the convergence argument is
// rigorous) and the Liar paradox (where the eigenvalue -1 analysis
// is exact). The weakest are the Aristotelian reframings, which
// are structural analogies that could be challenged.

(zeno_achilles_result | zeno_dichotomy_result | zeno_arrow_result | zeno_stadium_result |
 plato_forms_result | cave_result | aristotle_causes_result |
 liar_result | theseus_result | heraclitus_parmenides_result |
 socratic_aporia_result | golden_mean_result | divided_line_result |
 clinamen_result | potentiality_actuality_result
)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'all-pass' }]->(verdict: Verdict)
